<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="notes-week-02">
  <title>Module 2: Matrix Multiplication</title>
<objectives>
      <introduction>
        <p>We will explore the following concepts in this video:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><p>matrix multiplication</p></li>
        </ul>
      </introduction>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <p>
            Apply matrix algebra and the zero and identity matrices to solve and analyze matrix equations.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </objectives>

    <subsection xml:id="subsec-multiplication-definition">
      <title>Matrix Multiplication</title>
      
      <definition xml:id="def-matrix-product">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Let <m>A</m> be an <m>m \times n</m> matrix, and <m>B</m> be an <m>n \times p</m> matrix. The product <m>AB</m> is an <m>m \times p</m> matrix, equal to:
            <me>
              AB = A \begin{pmatrix} \vec{b}_1 \amp \cdots \amp \vec{b}_p \end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix} A\vec{b}_1 \amp \cdots \amp A\vec{b}_p \end{pmatrix}
            </me>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </definition>

      <exercise xml:id="ex-compute-product-1">
        <title>Example: Computing a Product</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Compute the following product:
            <me>
              C = AB = \begin{pmatrix} 2 \amp 0 \\ 1 \amp 1 \end{pmatrix} \begin{pmatrix} 2 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\ 3 \amp 4 \amp 0 \end{pmatrix}
            </me>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <answer>
          <p>
            <me>\begin{pmatrix} 4 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\ 5 \amp 4 \amp 0 \end{pmatrix}</me>
          </p>
        </answer>
        <solution>
          <p>
            Using the column definition:
            <ul>
              <li><p><m>A\vec{b}_1 = \begin{pmatrix} 2 \amp 0 \\ 1 \amp 1 \end{pmatrix} \begin{pmatrix} 2 \\ 3 \end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix} 4 \\ 5 \end{pmatrix}</m></p></li>
              <li><p><m>A\vec{b}_2 = \begin{pmatrix} 2 \amp 0 \\ 1 \amp 1 \end{pmatrix} \begin{pmatrix} 0 \\ 4 \end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix} 0 \\ 4 \end{pmatrix}</m></p></li>
              <li><p><m>A\vec{b}_3 = \begin{pmatrix} 2 \amp 0 \\ 1 \amp 1 \end{pmatrix} \begin{pmatrix} 0 \\ 0 \end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix} 0 \\ 0 \end{pmatrix}</m></p></li>
            </ul>
          </p>
        </solution>
      </exercise>
    </subsection>

    <subsection xml:id="subsec-row-column-rule">
      <title>Row-Column Rule</title>
      <p>
        The Row-Column Rule is a convenient way to calculate the product <m>AB</m>.
      </p>

      <assemblage xml:id="rule-row-column">
        <title>Row Column Method</title>
        <p>
          If <m>A \in \mathbb{R}^{m \times n}</m> has rows <m>\vec{a}_i</m>, and <m>B \in \mathbb{R}^{n \times p}</m> has columns <m>\vec{b}_j</m>, each element of the product <m>C = AB</m> is the dot product <m>c_{ij} = \vec{a}_i \cdot \vec{b}_j</m>.
        </p>
      </assemblage>

      <exercise xml:id="ex-row-column-calc">
        <title>Example: Row-Column Calculation</title>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Compute the following using the row-column method:
            <me>
              C = AB = \begin{pmatrix} 2 \amp 0 \\ 1 \amp 1 \end{pmatrix} \begin{pmatrix} 2 \amp 0 \amp 0 \\ 3 \amp 4 \amp 0 \end{pmatrix}
            </me>
          </p>
        </statement>
        <answer>
          <p><m>c_{11} = (2)(2) + (0)(3) = 4</m>, etc.</p>
        </answer>
      </exercise>
    </subsection>

    <summary>
      <p>We explored the following concepts:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><p>the identity and zero matrices</p></li>
        <li><p>matrix algebra: sums and products, scalar multiplies</p></li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        There are several ways of multiplying matrices that we explore in this class. This video introduced two methods.
      </p>
    </summary>
  
</section>
